76561197963816722,Recommended,298030,19843133,"Posted: 22 December, 2015",all,SnakesOnUrPlane,"RTS Classic!  Works in Windows 10!  Tons of Missions!  Cheap!  Buy it!Another favorite RTS from my childhood brought back to life!  Horraaayyy!Great strategy game with an interesting resource system, tons of units, tons of missions and hours of fun to be had!Was ahead of its time in so many ways when it came out back in 1997 and it still has so much to offer, especially with the cheap price tag!  The expansions are also included so you get TONS of single player missions and content.  Only real drawbacks are the 1997 era graphics and occasional clumsy unit pathing.If you can look past the graphics, the depth and difficulty really do rival that of most modern RTS games.  There is also no Auto-Save type feature so make sure to save your game often!  (and also use your commander to capture the warp gates, don't blow them up!  You'll thank me later...)Despite being an old game it works great in Windows 10 with no compatibilty problems or issues.  Just install and go!If you enjoy games like Command and Conquer, Warcraft 1 and 2, Starcraft, Supreme Commander, ect... Dont Skip this one!Truely a classic and not to be missed!"
,Recommended,298030,24830121,"Posted: 11 August, 2016",all,Lauri,"My parents got us a used PC with a Pentium I in 1997, which was nothing to scoff at in Eastern Europe at that time. The odds of the machine arriving with Total Annihilation on it's hard drive however seem incredible to me in hindsight. Of course initially, we, a 7-, 4- and 3-year-old didn't have much of a clue what we were doing playing this game, but I reckon by the time I was 10 or so I started getting better, reaching higher campaign missions. Never had the skill to complete the game back then though and I spent most of the time nuking the AI player on a random map with infinite metal, which was great fun in itself.Shortly before writing this review, I didn't know TA won Game of the Year in 1997, or even that it was made in 1997, but replaying this classic really made me realize why I was less impressed than my peers with later titles like Age of Empires 2 or Command & Conquer. TA had simply done so much better before them and I knew of it. I kid you not, Total Annihilation would be a strong title if it was released today. The mechanics of destruction feel so satisfying. Even the graphics don't look too bad. Most of today's titles cannot match it's diversity of units. TA had a pseudo-3D world where hills obstruct artillery fire, unit task queues and radar almost 20 years ago and I haven't even seen a similar veteran unit mechanic since. Even the story (I mean how cool is a Jupiter Brain?) is good and the soundtrack great. 7-year-old me in 1997 would have massively overestimated what a 2016 RTS title should look like based on this game, but I also get that if RTS-s would have progressed from TA to better as fast as things move in today's world, they would have become too complicated for most of the population by 1999 and everyone would have jumped ship for something simpler like Starcraft anyway.So yeah, it's highly debatable if any RTS has surpassed Cavedog's 1997 masterpiece, which works on a Pentium I, to this day."
