,Recommended,298030,21171993,"Posted: 13 February, 2016",all,James the Ivyark (Tansho1218),"Don't be fooled by my play time here on Steam. No other game in my entire collection has more hours put into it than this game right here. Spanning across many, manyyears, multiple computer systems, multiple OS, and countless mods, no other game I've ever owned has had as much attention in my life as this game right here.And now, it's on Steam.It's not the best port, I'll say that right now. The cracked unofficial WIndows 7 version I had running on my Windows 8,1 computer two years ago ran smoother than this one, but I digress, to finally have this game on a Windows 10 computer is pretty nifty. It does look a bit dated compared to many modern RTS, but at the same time it has aged very well. If you've ever played a ""Collect resources, build things, destroy your enemy"" RTS in the past decade or so, Total Anihilation will be very easy to get into. There are a few technical issues with this port, and some fixes to resolution need to be made for certain, plust it seems the game only has the ""official"" patches, meaning the unit limit cap is sadly smaller than I'm used to.For those who thrived off of modding this game, you'll understand what I mean. For those that don't, let's just say a 500 unit cap was ""small"" to us.Technical aspects aside, it is still a decent port and truly a game worthy of giving a look over. A rare gem of an RTS that was revolutionary back in a time dominated by Starcraft and Command & Conquer. Here you not only get the original legendary game itself, but all it's expansions and the final patch that was released shortly before Cavedog studios went belly up. For the price you're paying, it's well worth a play.Either for nostalgia's sake, curiosity, or if you're like me and never want to stop playing this game, OS be damned, then seriously, get it.End the war spanning the galaxy, and leave your enemy in total annihilation."
