76561198116377047,Recommended,298030,29495878,Posted: 25 January,all,XenogearsPS1,"This game simply oozes 90's charm, from gameplay to experiencing the limitations.A lot of people who are not long time RTS fans will probably get turned off by this game, just from looking at it.I do, however, encourage people to play this game.This game is still to this day years, decades even, ahead of it's time.From the notion of destroyed unit husks blocking unit movement, to the sheer scale of how powerful simple units can be.And for once in an RTS I actually feel like an Experimental unit, is Experimental.The Krogoth is an amazing unit that, while yes, does take a long time to build, can dish out serious firepower, however unlike Experimental units of today it is not Nigh-on invincible, and can die reletively easily, but can quickly pave the way for an army.The one big downside to the Krogoth is that only the CORE can build it, so if you're the ARM, you might want to build up your artillery.Although you'll probably never reach the point of actually building the Krogoth since it does take a considerable amount of time to build.The game also has a booming soundtrack, composed by the one and only Jeremy Soule, who also composed the music for Elder Scrolls, Guild Wars and other hit/Cult Classic titles.Very few composers such as Soule actually still compose today.Frank Klepaki is one such artist, alough his Command and Conquer work, will probably still be his best.The only game that I could recommend to ever coming close to TA, is probably Dark Reign, and even that doesn't come anywhere near the level this game produced.Pros:-The game is quite fluid, and offers quite a great deal of control over your units.-The future setting works in its favor instead of against it (Even to this day).-The music is masterfully crafted to suit the game's tone and ambition.-The art is quite unique and no 2 units look the same.-One of the very few RTS of its time to use more than 1 resource and be balanced-Maps are expertly crafted so that no one position feels, acts, or is the same.-Terrain actually plays a role in the game's combat.-Buildings actually have a wide degree of rotation (For the most part).Cons:-The game's flidity can be hindered by unexpected obstacles (UI, terrain, etc.).-While the art is incredibly unique, I do understand that it is a bit dated, namely how units and structures act.-Having 2 resources also means having more to protect in specific locations.-Asymmetry can lead to many problems on some of the maps, such as spawns.-Terrain is nice, but the tiniest of bumps can make a well planned base fall apart (So be very careful and wary)-Yes buildings have a surprising amount of rotation, however construction buildings can only be placed one way with minor rotation when placed.The game also came with a map editor and a ridiculous player system, both of which were not great.Building maps was a chore, and had many placement issues.The player count required 4 extra copies if you wanted to take advantage of all 8 player slots.TA Kingdoms improved on both of those features, but was unfortunately the ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ child, to many people, of the franchise.Although I quite liked Kingdoms, I just feel like it had too many units, and could have been better.Overall I give Total Annihilation a 10/10.Not even the flaws can keep me from loving this Masterpiece of ""Ahead of its time"" technology."
