,Recommended,298030,27746047,"Posted: 26 November, 2016",all,Pud354,"What a game!God knows how much CRT radiation I soaked up while glued to this game back at the turn of the century.Total Annihilation has finally made the jump to Steam, so I'm back for more play. I'm still damn impressed that this game from '97 supported widescreen (16:9) aspect ratios straight out of the box (Quite literally so, I remember first buying this game when it came in a cardboard box).Things that I remember impressed me about Total Annihilation back in 1999:-• 3D units• You could start forest fires• The ability to mine rocks for metal and harvest trees for surplus energy• The messy aftermath of significant battles (big battles left a big mess, metal wreckage of hundreds of destroyed units would litter large portions of the map)• You could often recycle the metal from the wreckage of destroyed unitsThe explosions in-game are also awesome, and will gratify most action junkies. When your units get destroyed, the explosions are screen-shaking, audibly thunderous, polygonal chunks of shrapnel debris hurtle through the air all over the place.When your commander unit is destroyed, it triggers an enormous nuclear explosion that causes significant 'splash damage', therefore when you sense an inevitable defeat you have an opportunity to rage quit in a kamikaze-esque enemy-destroying nuclear blaze of glory.If you like RTS games, science fiction and playing with nuclear weapons, you should check this game out."
